            "text": "\n\nThe name Hermanubis is a polytheophoric name, which combines the names of two deities (Hermes and Anubis) and was popular among males of middle and upper classes in Roman Egypt. This name refers to a specific deity that is independently attested, unlike other polytheophoric names.\n\nHermanubis is first attested in the Roman period and is found in various locations throughout Egypt, including Alexandria and Cynopolite. Alexandria is likely the birthplace and cult center of the fully anthropomorphic Hermanubis. It has been suggested that the name Hermanubis is closely associated with traditional Anubis and separating the two may not be warranted.\n\nThe onomastic evidence and documentary attestations provide more insights into the worship and significance of Hermanubis in the ancient world. Several forms of the personal name based on Hermanubis have been discovered with different suffixes, indicating various ways the name was modified in different contexts. Most of the names based on Hermanubis come from papyri dating to the second and third centuries AD, with the earliest example dating to AD 94. The name disappears after the fourth century, aligning with the decline in iconographical representations of Hermanubis.\n\nHermanubis was not only worshipped in Egypt but also found popularity outside of Egypt during the Roman period, with evidence of the name and cult of Hermanubis found in Macedonia, Thessalonike, and Carthage. This demonstrates the widespread influence and importance of Hermanubis in the ancient world.\n\nIn the Late Antique period, Hermanubis became a subject of satire in literary works, with his name associated with both Anubis the dog and Hermes the thief. This association added more layers to the understanding and interpretation of Hermanubis's role and symbolism in the ancient world.\n\nThe study of the name Hermanubis sheds light on the complex religious and cultural landscape of Graeco-Roman Egypt. The syncretic nature of the name and the deity it represents highlight the fluidity with which religious ideas and practices adapted and transformed across cultures and time periods."
